<br>
I'm pretty sure those aren't intended to be there as a weighting factor in determinging who gets hired or not.  They're there for auditing purposes.<br>
<br>
At the end of the year a company can look at the bigger picture of who applied, and who was hired / not hired from a race point of view, to ensure there aren't any large discrepancies.<br>
<br>
Let's say they note that their Los Angeles Branch and NY branch both had 400 white applicants, and 100 black ones.  The Los Angeles branch hired 90 white applicants, and 30 black ones.  The new york branch hired 90 black applicants and 0 white ones.   While it's true that it may just be coincidence and all 90 of those black applicants were the best qualified, it's also possible they have an HR person in that office who is hiring on the basis of race.<br>
<br>
They need that race information to check for that kind of stuff, and they need it on the applications rather than your new_hire paperwork because that way they can check for those kinds of discrepancies from the very beginning of the process (where people are hired or not hired).<br>
<br>
So while it can seem that they ask the question with intentions of discriminating, it's actually there for the purpose of ensuring that they're not discriminating.<br>
<br>
Will some people use that information against you when they're not supposed to consider it as part of the hiring process?  Definately.  Even just having an ethnic name counts against you in job applications.  Studies have been done where the exact same job application was submitted to various companies, one copy with a &quot;white&quot; sounding name, and one copy with an ethnic sounding name.  The &quot;white&quot; applicants received a much higher number of requests for a job interview.<br>
<br>
But without that checkbox there's no way for a company to tell if someone in HR is doing that kind of stuff.<br>
<br>
