Sadly I couldn't think of any particular examples of such forms that I've had to fill out, but one memory I do have of a similar, interesting situation was this:<br>
<br>
The mother of a friend of mine worked for Social Services (in England). One day she mentioned the vague details of her day at work to me and  my friend, saying how they could really use applications from another couple of Indian people <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(from India, rather than Native Americans)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in order to round out the numbers for a ... I forget the exact details, but it was a benefits discussion group, or something similar. I queried this, out of interest, wondering if it was because they needed representatives to offer the views of different parts of society. Her answer was that it was actually less for the representative views and more because they needed to fill a certain 'quota' from each race in order to satisfy internal regulations -- equal opportunities, they couldn't be seen to be discriminating, etc.<br>
<br>
I remarked that it seemed strange to be earmarking the spots for a people of a particular race if they weren't allowed to discriminate: surely if it were <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>truly</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> equal opportunity they would not ask for the applicant's race on the application form, the selection for the committee/group/<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>whatever it was</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would be performed entirely on a &quot;pulling names out of the hat&quot; basis. In this particular case, the response was that it was not the policy of Social Services to appear colour-blind: the group members were to be treated <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>as equals</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> but not <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>equally</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> -- a subtle but important difference:<br>
<br>
* <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>As equals</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->: no individual (or their opinion) was to be treated as superior or inferior to another.<br>
<br>
* Not treated <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>equally</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->: because Social Services had to acknowledge and recognise the cultural and social differences amongst the races.<br>
<br>
Though I could understand the difference and how it was important for a government agency to appear non-discriminatory and unbiased, it took me a while to figure out why the reasoning - though seemingly sound and fair - just didn't sit well with me.<br>
<br>
Finally it dawned on me: I still wasn't convinced that making sure a group of 10 people contained at least two Indians, at least one black person, and at least one asian, was not promoting the social and cultural divisions. Simply identifying a person by their heritage, skin colour, or culture was seeking to highlight the fact that people were different: it was not allowing for crossover between the races. It was still promoting the idea that we live in a black and white world, where grey is not an option. Still promoting the idea that people would rather marry within their own social, cultural and racial boundaries; implying a distrust, dislike or, at the very least, an notion of inequality between the races. That's what bugged me, and still does. If people are ever to consider themselves equals, if we're ever to overcome racial hatred, the very first step needs to be for &quot;racial checkboxes&quot; to disappear.<br>
